segments.text: It's going to be the graduate work.
Even if, say, undergraduate changes drastically, won't there always be the graduate?
Well, might be.
But even on certification for administration, you see, there are some alternative routes.
And
Oh, I think we face that as to whether we really are functional, whether we really serve a purpose or not.

But what I started out to say was it seems to me that there are changes in the teaching function at the elementary and secondary level, that the way in which information is handled, information management systems and so on.
that's affecting the way in which people function in elementary and secondary education.

And I think the important thing that we have to do is to be able to change our own operation and to function in a manner that's consistent, not expecting that they are doing it because we are teaching them how to do it.
we lead by running to catch up.
But I think the computerized methods of handling data certainly has changed this department a lot already.
We have some activities going on that build on this and perhaps may make some important contributions.
And so I think
Well, I think the way each of us as faculty members relate to our own students is quite different than it was 20 years ago.
And I think it will be in another 15, 20.
Can you just briefly expand on that a little bit?
Well, we hear people using this, the label facilitator of learning.

And maybe this has always been more true in graduate education, but I think we still are moving in the direction of faculty members trying to suggest how or where information and skills may come from, rather than the assumption that some way or other we personally can be responsible for that learning or that skill development.
And that will increase, you think?
I think so.
I think it has to.
Is there one last little anecdote or one last memoir, something that you might remember that stands out?
I know it's been a long time.
I don't know about any one thing.
You're thinking primarily in terms of the college itself.
True.
Are we within your department?
Are you personally?
I can't think of any one thing.
There's so many.
There are lots.
Have you ever written anything?
Do you have anything that you have kept over the years?
Any kind of diaries?
No.
No?
You have nothing?
No.
Well, Dr. Hawkins, this has been very enjoyable, and I thank you for your time, and I look forward to visiting with you.
